in the bill.

19:13.519 --> 19:18.724 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The NIH is the National
Institutes of Health,
and, basically, a lot of that
money will wind

19:18.758 --> 19:25.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up going into grants that go to
hospitals,
that go to universities, that go
to different

19:25.498 --> 19:27.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
labs to do research.

19:27.867 --> 19:32.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mostly -- you have all heard of
Joe Biden's
Cancer Moonshot.

19:32.938 --> 19:37.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's also a -- something
called the brain
initiative to sort of study the
brain more,

19:38.010 --> 19:42.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Alzheimer's, understand more
about how it
works, that you can prevent
things, and precision

19:42.381 --> 19:47.820 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
medicine, which is, to very much
simplify
it, a lot of genetics research.

19:47.853 --> 19:50.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Ed Silverman,
how about
the appropriations of this?

19:50.923 --> 19:55.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If it's not the Cancer Moonshot
or brain research,
and if it's not one of those
marquee things

19:55.828 --> 19:59.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that people care about, what
happens to the
rest of these huge amounts of
dollars, and

19:59.932 --> 20:02.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is it a guarantee that it will
happen year
after year?

20:02.368 --> 20:06.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ED SILVERMAN: Well, it all
sounds wonderful,
but the money has to be
appropriated.

20:06.439 --> 20:11.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, from day one, we have that
question hanging
over the entire effort.

20:11.210 --> 20:16.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Will that money actually go as
intended to
the right agencies, so it can do
the work?

20:16.782 --> 20:21.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Presumably, the FDA will get
funds, so they
can have more resources to take
on things

20:21.587 --> 20:24.390 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
like different approval
processes.

20:24.423 --> 20:26.025 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But the money's got to be there.

20:26.058 --> 20:30.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, if it's not appropriated,
well, then where
are we?

20:30.696 --> 20:35.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The agency will end up having
more work without
the added resources.

20:35.901 --> 20:40.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that's one of the
struggles that
has made the process over the
past few weeks

20:40.606 --> 20:46.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and months difficult to sort out
and really
feel comfortable that Congress
is going to

20:46.545 --> 20:48.314 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
do what it says it will do.

20:48.347 --> 20:50.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, Sydney
Lupkin, there
seems to be a shift away from
preventative

20:50.983 --> 20:52.818 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
measures in parts of the bill.

20:52.852 --> 20:59.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SYDNEY LUPKIN: What the bill
does is, is takes
away, I believe, $3.5 billion in
funding for

20:59.525 --> 21:06.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
preventative medicine, funds set
up under
Obamacare to study things like
Alzheimer's,

21:06.999 --> 21:09.401 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
chronic conditions,
hospital-acquired infection.

21:09.435 --> 21:17.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, the goal of that
fund is to
study these things so that then
it ultimately

21:17.543 --> 21:19.211 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
saves the health care system
money.

21:19.245 --> 21:23.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you can prevent something,
you don't have
to spend as much money treating
it.

21:23.482 --> 21:26.185 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that had been mandatory
funding.

21:26.218 --> 21:28.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So now it will get about 30
percent less than
it had.

21:28.787 --> 21:33.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Ed Silverman,
when it comes
to big pharma companies, drug
prices are something

21:33.058 --> 21:37.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that consumers care about,
something that
even hospitals and different
insurance companies

21:37.062 --> 21:38.430 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are trying to figure out a way
to decrease.

21:38.464 --> 21:40.199 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Does this tackle that at all?

21:40.232 --> 21:42.101 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ED SILVERMAN: No, not really.

21:42.134 --> 21:46.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that that's one
problem that Congress
is going to have to face up to,
whether it

21:46.639 --> 21:48.474 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
likes it or not.

21:48.507 --> 21:52.778 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It may not be in this
legislation, given that
the Senate vote appears to be
near, at this

21:52.811 --> 21:54.547 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
point anyway.

21:54.580 --> 21:59.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the bill doesn't really
address some of
the fundamental challenges and
issues that

21:59.218 --> 22:04.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are inherently problematic right
now in the
pricing system in this country.

22:04.890 --> 22:08.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is this just
the general
nature of such a large omnibus
bill?

22:08.861 --> 22:10.663 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ED SILVERMAN: Yes.

22:10.696 --> 22:15.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's almost the kitchen sink
approach, but
not quite, because Congress is
trying to pick

22:15.267 --> 22:20.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and choose a little bit of
what's easiest
and what it's most ideologically
comfortable

22:20.406 --> 22:22.308 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
pursuing.

22:22.341 --> 22:27.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For all the detail -- and there
are close
to 1,000 pages in this bill --
it really doesn't

22:27.580 --> 22:29.114 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
address everything.

22:29.148 --> 22:32.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, unfortunately, we discuss
pricing.

22:32.918 --> 22:37.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's not really mentioned here
in a way
that's going to be meaningful
for Americans.

22:37.489 --> 22:41.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And while there may be portions
that are helpful,
there are portions that are also
problematic,

22:41.827 --> 22:46.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as I mentioned before, with
concerns about
the FDA approval process and
what that means

22:46.565 --> 22:48.334 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
down the road for patient
safety.

22:48.367 --> 22:52.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right, Ed
Silverman
of STAT News and Sydney Lupkin
of Kaiser Health

22:52.805 --> 22:54.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
News, thanks so much.

22:54.406 --> 22:59.411 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SYDNEY LUPKIN: Thank you.

22:59.445 --> 23:04.516 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ED SILVERMAN: Thank you.

23:04.550 --> 23:07.853 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

23:07.886 --> 23:12.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
when it's not
just children who are distracted
by their

23:12.291 --> 23:19.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
devices; a guide to creating a
presidential
administration ready on day one;
and two jazz

23:19.798 --> 23:22.868 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
greats improvise their live
performance.

23:22.901 --> 23:29.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: how one for-profit
school model
is being tested to help
revitalize a school

23:29.942 --> 23:32.044 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
system in West Africa.

23:32.077 --> 23:38.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our story is in Liberia, a
country founded
by freed American slaves with a
history marked

23:38.050 --> 23:43.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by suffering, including two
recent civil wars
and the Ebola epidemic.

23:43.389 --> 23:48.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, the government is trying
to rebuild
a shattered nation, but a move
to employ a

23:48.193 --> 23:53.065 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for-profit American education
company has
drawn controversy.

23:53.098 --> 23:58.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Fred de
Sam Lazaro reports
as part of our weekly education
series on

23:58.637 --> 24:00.606 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Making the Grade.

24:00.639 --> 24:08.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: It's Friday
morning, and
the children at this public
elementary school

24:08.414 --> 24:13.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are singing patriotic songs that
honor their
country's founding by freed
American slaves.

24:13.719 --> 24:20.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And as the U.S.-inspired flag is
being raised,
so too are hopes about how
public education

24:20.459 --> 24:23.796 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can be quickly and dramatically
improved.

24:23.829 --> 24:29.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These students are part of a
grand experiment
to see if a private for-profit
U.S.-based

24:29.535 --> 24:35.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
company can turn things around
in a nation
utterly destroyed by a 14-year
long civil

24:35.107 --> 24:38.577 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
war and a recent battle with
Ebola.

24:38.610 --> 24:43.682 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president of Liberia has
called the country's
education system a mess.

24:43.716 --> 24:45.517 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What did she mean?

24:45.551 --> 24:53.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Consider this statistic: In
2013, not one
of 25,000 high school graduates
in this country

24:53.625 --> 24:59.098 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
managed to pass the college
entrance exam
for the University of Liberia.

24:59.131 --> 25:04.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The experiment to bring in
private partners
was designed by Education
Minister George

25:04.069 --> 25:09.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Werner, who took office 15
months ago, hired
by the president, he says, to
act quickly.

25:09.174 --> 25:13.712 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GEORGE WERNER, Liberian
Education Minister:
If we stayed the course,
followed the traditional

25:13.746 --> 25:19.118 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ways of doing things, we
wouldn't catch up
with our neighboring
counterparts.

25:19.151 --> 25:24.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Werner had
been impressed
during a visit to Kenya, where
the U.S. company

25:24.623 --> 25:30.596 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Bridge International Academies
operates more
than 350 private schools.

25:30.629 --> 25:36.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Liberia, where average annual
household
income is less than $500, Werner
knew most

25:36.268 --> 25:41.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
families could not afford the
monthly $6 fee
that Bridge charges per child in
those other

25:41.874 --> 25:43.208 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
countries.

25:43.242 --> 25:44.543 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But he had an idea.

25:44.576 --> 25:51.283 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GEORGE WERNER: What if we had a
hybrid for
public and private?

25:51.316 --> 25:57.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are certain things that
the private
sector does better than the
public sector.

25:57.222 --> 26:03.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Government can come up with the
policies,
but management systems and
service delivery,

26:03.061 --> 26:06.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
often, the private sector does
better than
the government.

26:06.298 --> 26:12.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Werner hired
seven private
organizations to run a total of
94 primary

26:12.304 --> 26:13.272 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
schools.

26:13.305 --> 26:18.510 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bridge, the only for-profit,
runs 24 of them.

26:18.544 --> 26:20.612 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Josh Nathan is the company's
academic director.

26:20.646 --> 26:22.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSH NATHAN, Academic Director,
Bridge International
Academies: What the government
has done in

26:22.314 --> 26:24.116 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Liberia is quite courageous.

26:24.149 --> 26:27.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They've said, we're struggling
with providing
children this basic right, so
what we want

26:27.886 --> 26:33.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to do is look around, look
inside Liberia
and outside Liberia, at other
people who are

26:33.392 --> 26:36.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
succeeding in providing children
with an excellent
education.

26:36.361 --> 26:40.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: The
government agreed
to pay the companies directly,
so education

26:40.866 --> 26:43.035 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
remains free for families.

26:43.068 --> 26:48.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The companies also provide
uniforms, which
are required at public schools
and whose cost

26:48.073 --> 26:50.275 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
keeps many from attending.

26:50.309 --> 26:56.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When we visited the Bridge
school in Kendaja,
the semester was only two weeks
underway,

26:56.081 --> 26:58.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and many of the uniforms had not
yet arrived.

26:58.050 --> 27:00.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAGDALENE BROWN, Bridge School
Principal:
Today is a wonderful day for us
too.

27:00.319 --> 27:05.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Principal
Magdalene Brown
said the improvements were
already very apparent.

27:05.123 --> 27:09.294 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For one thing, there's a much
longer school
day.

27:09.328 --> 27:11.163 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Last year, it was just four
hours a day.

27:11.196 --> 27:19.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAGDALENE BROWN: Bridge has us
come to school
much earlier, like we at 7:30,
and then Bridge

27:19.238 --> 27:23.542 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have us stay on until 3:30 every
day.

27:23.575 --> 27:26.512 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that means the children will
learn better.

27:26.545 --> 27:31.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Even the
students seem
to like it more, including
15-year-old Mercy

27:31.750 --> 27:32.818 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Freeman.

27:32.851 --> 27:33.719 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MERCY FREEMAN, Student: We come
to school
on time.

27:33.752 --> 27:35.020 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We sit in class.

27:35.053 --> 27:39.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And school
actually runs
like a school?

27:39.224 --> 27:40.893 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MERCY FREEMAN: Yes.

27:40.926 --> 27:45.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: There are
also new rules,
such as no more corporal
punishment.

27:45.330 --> 27:50.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And along with new textbooks,
every teacher
is given a computer tablet and
is required

27:50.502 --> 27:54.473 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to stick to pre-loaded lesson
plans.

27:54.506 --> 28:00.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Critics of this so-called
school-in-a-box
approach say it encourages
robotic teaching

28:00.612 --> 28:04.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and has allowed Bridge in other
countries
to hire cheaper, less qualified
instructors.

28:04.950 --> 28:11.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's less of an issue in
Liberia, where
Bridge schools retrain teachers
who are already

28:11.123 --> 28:16.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
working in the school system and
where many
had their own education
disrupted by the civil

28:16.728 --> 28:17.996 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
war.

28:18.030 --> 28:21.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In this building, teachers
seemed grateful
for the guidance.

28:21.833 --> 28:25.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Amos Jumanine has taught for
seven years,
but says he was a late bloomer.

28:25.737 --> 28:28.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMOS JUMANINE, Teacher: I was 17
years when
I started ABCs.

28:28.440 --> 28:33.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: You went to
kindergarten
learning your ABCs when you were
17?

28:33.812 --> 28:35.547 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
AMOS JUMANINE: Yeah, 17.

28:35.581 --> 28:40.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: He is
hopeful the new
partnership will be good for the
students.

28:40.519 --> 28:46.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he is adamant on one thing
that needs
to change: Teachers need to be
paid more money,

28:46.291 --> 28:49.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
especially now that they're
required to work
longer hours.

28:49.294 --> 28:51.496 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMOS JUMANINE: I cannot afford
to buy food
for myself.

28:51.530 --> 28:53.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Financially,
it's very
difficult?

28:53.632 --> 28:54.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
AMOS JUMANINE: Yes, financially.

28:54.700 --> 28:56.335 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Very
difficult.

28:56.368 --> 28:58.103 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
AMOS JUMANINE: Very difficult.

28:58.136 --> 29:02.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Teachers in
Liberia earn
about $100 a month, and many say
they take

29:02.574 --> 29:05.077 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
second jobs just to make ends
meet.

29:05.110 --> 29:11.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That contributes to one of the
biggest problems
in Liberian schools: chronic
teacher absenteeism.

29:11.149 --> 29:14.653 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Not only are teachers routinely
absent.

29:14.686 --> 29:20.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many really never existed, just
their names
on paychecks issued by the
schools.

29:21.026 --> 29:27.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Education Minister Werner says
he's purged
about 1,300 so-called ghost
teachers, saving

29:28.000 --> 29:30.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
$2 million that was being
siphoned away in
fraud.

29:31.003 --> 29:34.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSH NATHAN: The president
herself has acknowledged
that this is a system that is
really a mess.

29:34.339 --> 29:38.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Josh Nathan
says the Bridge
schools use software in the
teachers' tablets

29:38.276 --> 29:40.145 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to track their daily attendance.

29:40.178 --> 29:44.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSH NATHAN: We think this is
incredibly important
to creating accountability and
being able

29:44.182 --> 29:47.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to watch every single day, where
are our teachers,
are they where they need to be?

29:47.786 --> 29:51.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: For their
part, the teachers
union is strongly opposed to the
partnership

29:51.590 --> 29:53.291 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
program.

29:53.325 --> 29:58.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It points out that these new
schools have
smaller class size, around 45 to
55 pupils,

29:58.330 --> 30:04.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and receive about $10 to $15
more per student
than regular public schools.

30:04.369 --> 30:08.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Union leaders say their teachers
could get
even better outcomes than Bridge
if they were

30:08.473 --> 30:10.942 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
given that extra money and
smaller classes.

30:10.976 --> 30:16.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you had the right conditions
and a better
salary, a lot of the problem
would be solved?

30:16.181 --> 30:17.516 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARY MULBAH, Teachers Union:
Yes.

30:17.549 --> 30:20.452 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And when you
argued this,
what were you told?

30:20.485 --> 30:23.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARY MULBAH: The ministry,
they're not even
listening to the teachers.

30:23.789 --> 30:29.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Mary Mulbah
blames corruption
at the ministry for hiring the
ghost teachers

30:29.161 --> 30:34.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and alleges the ministry is
using its purges
to target union activists.

30:34.866 --> 30:39.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Immanuel Morris, who was in a
government program
to train and hire new teachers,
says his name

30:39.838 --> 30:40.806 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was deleted.

30:40.839 --> 30:42.274 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Are you a ghost?

30:42.307 --> 30:43.742 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
IMMANUEL MORRIS, Union Activist:
I'm not a
ghost, and I can prove that.

30:43.775 --> 30:45.477 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: They're
calling you a
ghost.

30:45.510 --> 30:46.478 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
IMMANUEL MORRIS: That is what
I'm saying.

30:46.511 --> 30:47.479 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And you're
not a ghost?

30:47.512 --> 30:49.381 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
IMMANUEL MORRIS: I'm not a
ghost.

30:49.414 --> 30:52.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Union
leaders also question
whether such programs could be
scaled up to

30:52.951 --> 30:58.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
serve the 2,750 elementary
schools across
the country.

30:58.156 --> 31:03.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Minister Werner knows there are
risks, but
says the government has a moral
obligation

31:03.261 --> 31:04.529 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to take drastic measures.

31:04.563 --> 31:08.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GEORGE WERNER: It's not a
panacea.

31:08.567 --> 31:09.668 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it may just not work.

31:09.701 --> 31:12.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we should not just fold our
arms and do
nothing.

31:12.571 --> 31:17.642 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO:
Sixty-one-year-old Marie
Jaynes couldn't agree more.

31:17.676 --> 31:20.612 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She herself had to drop out of
school in fourth
grade.

31:20.645 --> 31:26.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She now sells water at the side
of the road
to support her three
grandchildren, their

31:26.885 --> 31:28.987 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
parents killed in the civil war.

31:29.020 --> 31:33.525 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jaynes says the new school will
give her grandchildren
a better life than she has had.

31:33.558 --> 31:38.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARIE JAYNES, Grandmother: What
hope for them
is to go far in school, for them
to know the

31:38.864 --> 31:40.499 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
importance of school.

31:40.532 --> 31:44.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: They are the
first of
three generations in her family
that might

31:44.569 --> 31:48.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
enjoy the privileges of at least
a primary
school education.

31:49.007 --> 31:52.878 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," this is
Fred de Sam
Lazaro in Kendaja, Liberia.

31:52.911 --> 31:59.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A version of this
story aired
on the PBS program "Religion &amp;
Ethics Newsweekly."

31:59.918 --> 32:05.290 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Fred's reporting is a
partnership with the
Under-Told Stories Project at
University of

32:05.323 --> 32:10.128 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
St. Thomas in Minnesota.

32:10.162 --> 32:22.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: We have spent
our share
of time looking at how kids and
teens spend

32:22.374 --> 32:24.042 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
time with their screens.

32:24.075 --> 32:27.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now there's a new survey that
finds their
parents have some of the same
habits.

32:27.712 --> 32:32.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The study, which asked for
feedback from 1,700
parents of children age 8 to 18,
found adults

32:32.851 --> 32:38.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
spending more than nine hours a
day themselves
looking at video screens.

32:38.056 --> 32:42.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yet, even as they are worried
about how much
time their children spend
watching screens,

32:42.794 --> 32:47.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nearly 80 percent of parents
felt they were
good role models for their kids
when it came

32:47.999 --> 32:49.701 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to this.

32:49.734 --> 32:52.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jim Steyer is the founder and
CEO of Common
Sense Media, which conducted the
survey.

32:52.304 --> 32:54.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My jaw is still on the floor
about the nine
hours.

32:54.973 --> 32:56.341 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That seems unbelievable.

32:56.374 --> 32:58.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have got to be counting
stuff that I do
at work and my laptop.

32:58.877 --> 33:00.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES STEYER, Founder and CEO,
Common Sense
Media: It's astounding to me,
too.

33:00.612 --> 33:01.913 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I thought it was going to be
about four hours.

33:01.947 --> 33:03.014 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

33:03.048 --> 33:04.382 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I thought it would be four,
four-and-a-half-hours.

33:04.416 --> 33:07.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The truth is, though, it's only
an hour-and-a-half
of work time.

33:07.619 --> 33:12.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So that means seven hours and 45
minutes per
day, the average American parent
is spending

33:12.123 --> 33:13.992 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with screen media at home.

33:14.025 --> 33:15.327 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It was shocking.

33:15.360 --> 33:17.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they think they're good role
models.

33:17.162 --> 33:21.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, that's the
other part,
that while they try to tell
their kids, get

33:21.399 --> 33:26.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
off your phone and pay attention
and talk
to each other, under the table,
they're checking

33:26.238 --> 33:27.205 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
their e-mail.

33:27.239 --> 33:28.840 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMES STEYER: That's exactly
right.

33:28.874 --> 33:31.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, actually, I do think that's
what the
bottom line about this whole
survey is.

33:31.309 --> 33:33.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
First of all, nobody ever asked
parents.

33:33.111 --> 33:36.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you mentioned in the opening,
we have looked
at how much time kids do,
whether they're

33:36.414 --> 33:39.584 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
age 8 to 18 or zero to 8, but
nobody ever
asked parents.

33:39.618 --> 33:41.686 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I thought parents were much
more controlled.

33:41.720 --> 33:44.322 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the truth is, everybody is
addicted to
their devices these days.

33:44.356 --> 33:47.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And you
actually started
to break it down by income level
and ethnicity.

33:47.292 --> 33:48.493 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JAMES STEYER: Right.

33:48.526 --> 33:50.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You started to
see some
patterns emerged.

33:50.295 --> 33:54.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JAMES STEYER: The most
interesting pattern
is that Latino families are more
than twice

33:54.099 --> 34:00.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as concerned about and engaged
in their kids'
media consumption as white or
African-American

34:00.305 --> 34:02.040 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
or Asian American parents.

34:02.073 --> 34:06.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, there is a big cultural
difference, and
I think a very laudable one, in
the Latino

34:07.012 --> 34:08.513 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
community.

34:08.546 --> 34:13.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're more concerned about
cyber-bullying,
about pornography, about issues.

34:13.919 --> 34:15.754 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then they set tougher
limits.

34:15.787 --> 34:20.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I actually think it shows a
cultural tendency
toward family that's good, that
we should

34:20.392 --> 34:22.160 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
all learn from.

34:22.193 --> 34:24.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: It also seems
to be that
the more they know about what
their kids are

34:24.062 --> 34:25.030 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
doing, the less worried they
are.

34:25.063 --> 34:26.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMES STEYER: I think that's
true in general.

34:26.665 --> 34:29.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Your kids are going to get older
sooner than
you think, Hari.

34:29.334 --> 34:36.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when you do know more, I
think you relax
and think, I can teach them
judgment and values.

34:36.207 --> 34:41.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think parents today are
just blown away
by the surfeit of digital media
platforms

34:41.780 --> 34:43.581 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that we all live with.

34:43.615 --> 34:47.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They don't understand Snapchat
or Instagram,
but they're using them
themselves more than

34:47.886 --> 34:48.853 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they were once.

34:48.887 --> 34:50.922 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think the number, nine hours,
is shocking.

34:50.956 --> 34:55.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TV is still the number-one
medium that parents
like, but they are spending time
on the same

34:55.927 --> 34:57.395 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
platforms that their kids are.

34:57.429 --> 34:59.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And how do
they feel about
social media for their kids?

35:00.031 --> 35:00.999 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JAMES STEYER: Mixed.

35:01.032 --> 35:02.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Very mixed.

35:02.634 --> 35:04.803 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I actually think that's
really true about
media and technology in general.

35:04.836 --> 35:10.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the one hand, parents think
their kids
have to learn technology for
education, for

35:10.842 --> 35:12.510 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
jobs, for 21st century skills.

35:12.544 --> 35:16.181 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Like, 94 percent of parents
agree that technology
is really good.

35:16.214 --> 35:21.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the other hand, they're
worried about tech
addiction, lack of sleep,
cyber-bullying,

35:21.319 --> 35:23.054 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pornography, all the downsides.

35:23.088 --> 35:25.156 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it's a nuanced picture.

35:25.190 --> 35:27.959 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think it reflects the way
I feel as
a parent of four kids, too.

35:27.993 --> 35:29.461 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have got to be there.

35:29.494 --> 35:31.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And actually they have to
understand social
media.

35:31.763 --> 35:33.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I'm worried about what might
happen to
them.

35:33.865 --> 35:37.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And in this
day and age,
you go to classrooms, so many of
them are

35:37.235 --> 35:39.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wired or wireless, and kids are
connected
to laptops.

35:39.971 --> 35:41.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sometimes, they're bringing that
software
home.

35:41.973 --> 35:43.975 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's necessary for homework.

35:44.009 --> 35:45.076 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JAMES STEYER: That's right.

35:45.110 --> 35:46.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we believe strongly in that
at Common
Sense.

35:46.611 --> 35:49.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We now have 130,000 member
schools.

35:49.314 --> 35:52.984 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, the vast majority of
American schools
are members of Common Sense
Media and use

35:53.018 --> 35:57.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a curriculum we developed with
Harvard professors
called Digital Literacy and
Citizenship.

35:57.922 --> 36:05.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, technology -- comma -- used
wisely -- comma
-- is an extraordinary
educational tool.

36:05.230 --> 36:08.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But used inappropriately, it can
cause all
sorts of problems.

36:08.400 --> 36:11.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I actually think that's
clearly now as
true for parents as it is for
our kids.

36:11.836 --> 36:15.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Were there any
clear rules
of the road that these parents
advocated for?

36:15.673 --> 36:17.475 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JAMES STEYER: Well, it's
interesting.

36:17.509 --> 36:20.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you mentioned in the opening,
nearly 80
percent of parents say that
they're good role

36:20.278 --> 36:21.780 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
models.

36:21.813 --> 36:25.750 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But you would think, therefore,
that they're
doing three or four hours a day.

36:25.784 --> 36:29.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The truth is, the big thing that
we have seen
and we have promoted at Common
Sense is what

36:29.621 --> 36:35.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we call device-free dinner,
meaning have family
meals, not just dinner, but all
family meals.

36:35.160 --> 36:39.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Get rid of the phones, get rid
of your laptops,
get rid of all those devices,
and just be

36:39.831 --> 36:44.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there with your kids, and create
sacred spaces,
what our colleague at MIT Sherry
Turkle refers

36:44.769 --> 36:49.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to as sacred spaces, where there
is just no
device in between you and your
children.

36:49.441 --> 36:53.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, parents say they do that,
but the numbers
sort of belie that.

36:53.778 --> 36:56.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What about any
kind of long-term
effects?

36:56.714 --> 37:00.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Relatively speaking, smartphones
are still
pretty new in the long arc of
technology.

37:00.251 --> 37:02.120 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JAMES STEYER: Yes.

37:02.153 --> 37:06.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, I think it has an
enormous impact
on everything from empathy -- if
you're constantly

37:06.491 --> 37:11.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
looking down at your phone, as
opposed to
talking to your kid, I think it
has an effect

37:11.529 --> 37:13.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on your relationship with that
child.

37:13.465 --> 37:17.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think, with younger kids,
there's brain
development issues.

37:17.502 --> 37:21.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At my age, I don't -- whatever
little brain
I have is probably developed as
much as it's

37:21.439 --> 37:23.308 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
going to be.

37:23.341 --> 37:27.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think it has to do with
long-term effects
on family relationships, human
interaction.

37:27.479 --> 37:31.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the positives are the
educational opportunities,
the chance to connect with
people around the

37:31.749 --> 37:33.651 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
world.

37:33.685 --> 37:37.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's all about how you use
it, and I actually
think setting limits, too, and a
healthy media

37:37.956 --> 37:39.457 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
diet.

37:39.491 --> 37:41.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right, Jim
Steyer, Common
Sense Media, thanks so much.

37:41.593 --> 37:51.269 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMES STEYER: Great to be here,
Hari.

37:51.302 --> 37:58.510 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: With
president-elect Trump
focused on preparing to take
office in January,

37:58.543 --> 38:02.614 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we return now to the transition
process from
one president to the next.

38:02.647 --> 38:08.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I sat down recently with Max
Stier, no relation
to the Jim Steyer we just heard
from.

38:08.386 --> 38:13.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Max Stier is president and CEO
of the Partnership
for Public Service and an expert
on presidential

38:13.491 --> 38:15.493 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
transitions.

38:15.527 --> 38:17.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Max Stier, welcome to the
"NewsHour."

38:17.395 --> 38:20.598 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You have published this
presidential transition
guide.

38:20.632 --> 38:25.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you have also called the
Trump transition
the biggest takeover in history
of an organization.

38:25.770 --> 38:27.272 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Seriously?

38:27.305 --> 38:29.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAX STIER, President and CEO,
Partnership
for Public Service: Seriously.

38:29.107 --> 38:32.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You think about the United
States government,
you're talking about $4 trillion
in spend,

38:32.977 --> 38:36.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
four million people, when you
include the
military, hundreds of different
operating

38:36.614 --> 38:38.516 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
entities and the agencies.

38:38.550 --> 38:43.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have got 4,000 political
appointees; 1,100
of them have to go through
Senate confirmation.

38:43.922 --> 38:48.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No other democracy has that kind
of penetration
of political appointees in
government.

38:48.960 --> 38:54.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a phenomenally complex,
important, and
critical process that is
typically very ill-understood.

38:54.832 --> 38:59.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, what does a
president-elect
coming in and his or her team,
what do they

38:59.237 --> 39:01.639 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have to get right from the
start?

39:01.673 --> 39:05.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAX STIER: Right from the start,
they have
to understand how difficult this
process is,

39:05.543 --> 39:10.014 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and that history is not
sufficient guidance
for what has to come going
forward.

39:10.048 --> 39:13.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Transition is also the point of
maximum vulnerability
for our country.

39:13.384 --> 39:17.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a post-9/11 world, getting
this right is
essential, not just for the
president to be

39:17.789 --> 39:22.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
able to achieve their policy
objectives, but
also to keep us safe.

39:22.293 --> 39:26.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Job number one is to get your
team on the
field when the clock starts, and
that means

39:26.531 --> 39:28.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
January 20 at noon.

39:28.733 --> 39:31.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's not going to be
everybody, but
our view is, you should have
your full White

39:31.703 --> 39:36.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
House in place and at least your
top 100 Senate
confirmed positions that are
leading the agencies

39:36.841 --> 39:38.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that are critical to running
government.

39:38.676 --> 39:43.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we look at
this and we
hear some of the names that have
been announced

39:43.281 --> 39:46.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
so far by Donald Trump.

39:46.251 --> 39:50.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most of them either haven't
served in government
or, if they have, they haven't
served in the

39:50.188 --> 39:51.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
executive branch.

39:51.322 --> 39:53.091 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Why does that matter?

39:53.124 --> 39:57.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAX STIER: It matters because
running these
agencies is a phenomenally
difficult task.

39:57.195 --> 40:01.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so when you think about
running a large
organization, and you want
people who have

40:01.232 --> 40:05.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
done that before, it's harder in
the government
than it is in the private
sector.

40:05.536 --> 40:10.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Truth is that almost -- and I
mean this -- almost
nobody ever comes into the
government at the

40:10.708 --> 40:13.811 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
senior levels with having the
experience of
having done it before.

40:13.845 --> 40:14.812 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's new for everybody.

40:14.846 --> 40:16.547 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The learning curve is very
steep.

40:16.581 --> 40:20.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One exception, obviously, is
someone like
Elaine Chao, who's both at
Transportation

40:20.718 --> 40:21.686 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and at Labor.

40:21.719 --> 40:22.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

40:22.720 --> 40:23.688 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAX STIER: But that truly is the
exception.

40:23.721 --> 40:26.324 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
These are incredibly hard jobs
to get right.

40:26.357 --> 40:30.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And as much experience as you
have is good,
but you really need to
contextualize that

40:30.828 --> 40:33.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
experience to specific issues
you face in
government.

40:34.032 --> 40:35.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that requires a lot of
learning fast.

40:35.867 --> 40:40.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you assess
so far -- I
know we're still early in the
process -- that

40:40.672 --> 40:44.442 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Trump team is doing in terms
of getting
its arms around what's coming?

40:44.475 --> 40:47.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAX STIER: So, I think that they
have a long
distance still to travel.

40:47.512 --> 40:50.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They did some very, very good
pre-election
planning.

40:51.015 --> 40:52.350 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Now they're at game time.

40:52.383 --> 40:54.185 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're obviously naming a punch
of people.

40:54.218 --> 40:58.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But naming them isn't the same
thing as getting
them into the seats.

40:58.389 --> 40:59.891 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Clearing conflicts have to
happen.

40:59.924 --> 41:02.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have to go through the
Senate confirmation
process.

41:02.260 --> 41:04.762 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have a background checks
that the FBI
does.

41:04.796 --> 41:07.665 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's a very difficult process
in the ordinary
course.

41:07.699 --> 41:12.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for a number of these
people, especially
with high net worth, very
complicated holdings,

41:12.103 --> 41:13.504 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it makes it even harder.

41:13.538 --> 41:15.340 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have got a long distance to
travel.

41:15.373 --> 41:19.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the key here is not to
focus on single
individuals, but, one, have they
adopted the

41:19.944 --> 41:21.813 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
right goals?

41:21.846 --> 41:25.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, again, that means getting
their leaders
in place at the beginning,
coming to the table

41:25.216 --> 41:29.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with a management agenda,
starting right with
Congress and with other critical
stakeholders,

41:29.721 --> 41:32.090 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
like the career work force,
which they will
have to run.

41:32.123 --> 41:33.925 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Those are the things that they
need to set
up now.

41:33.958 --> 41:37.562 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then they need to
demonstrate this in
the next couple of months, that
they're ready

41:37.595 --> 41:39.263 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to go when they own the place.

41:39.297 --> 41:44.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And how are these
skills that
are required right now different
from the

41:44.435 --> 41:45.770 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
skills in the private sector?

41:45.803 --> 41:48.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, Donald Trump clearly
comes out of
the business world.

41:48.840 --> 41:51.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many of the people he's named
come out of
the business world with these
early names.

41:51.542 --> 41:52.510 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAX STIER: Right.

41:52.543 --> 41:53.644 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: There are more to
come.

41:53.678 --> 41:57.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But what's different in the
muscles that are
needed?

41:57.181 --> 41:58.950 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MAX STIER: It's a great
question.

41:58.983 --> 42:04.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I would say one positive is
that the government
does need smart business
principles.

42:04.722 --> 42:08.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when you get someone who has
run an organization
in the private sector in a good
way, there

42:09.026 --> 42:11.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are great principles that can be
transferred
over.

42:11.763 --> 42:16.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They need the good principles,
but government
cannot be run like a business,
so some differences.

42:16.334 --> 42:18.169 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Starts with Congress.

42:18.202 --> 42:20.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when you're in the private
sector, you
don't have to worry about a
board of directors

42:20.505 --> 42:25.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that is in conflict with each
other, that
doesn't provide you with a
budget, that doesn't

42:25.610 --> 42:27.211 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have a capital budget.

42:27.245 --> 42:30.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The working-with-Congress piece
is phenomenally
different and very complicated.

42:30.815 --> 42:33.451 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have a high degree of
transparency.

42:33.484 --> 42:35.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have multiple different
stakeholders.

42:35.486 --> 42:39.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you have scale that you
almost never see
in the private sector that you
have in government.

42:39.957 --> 42:45.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And just quickly,
finally,
Max Stier, to the public
watching out there

42:45.530 --> 42:51.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who doesn't know a lot or really
isn't that
interested in the inner workings
of government,

42:51.135 --> 42:52.603 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
why should they care about this?

42:52.637 --> 42:53.971 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAX STIER: Right.

42:54.005 --> 42:55.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, fundamentally, this is --
it all begins
in the beginning.

42:55.840 --> 42:59.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you get the beginning wrong,
you're playing
catchup for the rest of your
administration.

42:59.644 --> 43:02.313 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It starts with national
security.

43:02.346 --> 43:04.482 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's the core function of our
government.

43:04.515 --> 43:07.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Again, transition is the point
of maximum
vulnerability for our
government.

43:07.618 --> 43:09.420 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have a lot of enemies out
there.

43:09.454 --> 43:13.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're looking to see whether
or not that
baton handoff is clean, that the
new leadership

43:13.558 --> 43:14.525 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is actually ready.

43:14.559 --> 43:15.893 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, that's where it begins.

43:15.927 --> 43:18.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's also all the other
things we get
from our government.

43:18.596 --> 43:23.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In order for that to happen
right, we need
the new president to be ready on
day one,

43:23.601 --> 43:28.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people in place, right goals, a
management
agenda, and understanding how
the whole process

43:28.973 --> 43:30.675 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
works.

43:30.708 --> 43:33.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Max Stier with
the Partnership
for Public Service, thank you so
much for

43:33.678 --> 43:34.645 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
coming by.

43:34.679 --> 43:38.516 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAX STIER: Thank you very much.

43:38.549 --> 43:51.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Next: how a
passion for
improvisation can make beautiful
music.

43:51.496 --> 43:55.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Two jazz stalwarts rejoin forces
for a new
album and a series of concerts.

43:55.500 --> 43:58.269 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has the story.

43:58.302 --> 44:11.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The song, Hoagy
Carmichael's
1938 ballad "The Nearness of
You," performed

44:11.382 --> 44:26.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as a kind of conversation
between two master
musicians who happen to be peers
and friends,

44:26.297 --> 44:29.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
saxophonist Joshua Redman,
pianist Brad Mehldau.

44:29.367 --> 44:32.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRAD MEHLDAU, Pianist: If you're
going to
play a ballad with someone, and
you want it

44:32.703 --> 44:37.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be anything deeper than this
just sort
of surface, you're going to have
to be vulnerable

44:37.475 --> 44:38.843 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for the other person.

44:38.876 --> 44:40.511 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's what the audience
wants to see,
too.

44:40.545 --> 44:41.512 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOSHUA REDMAN, Saxophonist: Yes.

44:41.546 --> 44:42.513 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jazz is all about vulnerability.

44:42.547 --> 44:43.514 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BRAD MEHLDAU: So, you got to...

44:43.548 --> 44:44.515 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Vulnerability?

44:44.549 --> 44:45.516 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

44:45.550 --> 44:46.951 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BRAD MEHLDAU: Yes.

44:46.984 --> 44:48.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSHUA REDMAN: I think so, yes,
because we're
improvising, you know?

44:48.786 --> 44:52.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we're not coming to the
bandstand with
a preconceived notion of what
we're going

44:52.790 --> 44:54.625 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to play.

44:54.659 --> 44:59.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have to be open and available
and vulnerable
to really make that connection
with ourselves

44:59.931 --> 45:01.732 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and with the other musician.

45:01.766 --> 45:07.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Redman, 47, and
Mehldau, 46,
have been filling concert halls
and jazz clubs,

45:07.638 --> 45:15.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on their own, as band leaders,
and together,
for more than 20 years.

45:15.680 --> 45:20.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This fall, they have joined
forces again in
a recent performance at New
York's Jazz at

45:20.184 --> 45:28.426 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Lincoln Center, and on a
newly-released album
titled "Nearness," a mix of
original material

45:28.459 --> 45:32.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and jazz standards recorded live
on tour in
2011.

45:32.096 --> 45:39.103 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOSHUA REDMAN: I feel so
fortunate to be able
to make the music that I believe
in, and to

45:39.136 --> 45:44.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
get up there every night and
just play from
the soul and go for it.

45:44.508 --> 45:49.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRAD MEHLDAU: As an improvising
musician,
I really feel committed to not
going out there

45:49.614 --> 45:51.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and playing some nonsense for
people, you
know?

45:51.148 --> 45:52.116 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

45:52.149 --> 45:53.884 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRAD MEHLDAU: There's a bit of a
script.

45:53.918 --> 45:57.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have some plan, but what they
want to hear
is, they really want to hear us
try to be

45:57.321 --> 45:58.289 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
creative.

45:58.322 --> 46:00.458 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Both men came to
music early.

46:00.491 --> 46:06.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Redman, in California, was
raised by his dancer
mother, and is the son of
well-known saxophonist

46:06.631 --> 46:13.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dewey Redman, Mehldau in Florida
and Connecticut
in a family home never without a
piano.

46:13.871 --> 46:19.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They arrived separately in New
York in the
early 1990s, where each found
his own early

46:19.744 --> 46:21.379 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
success.

46:21.412 --> 46:26.350 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We spoke recently at the
Steinway Piano Showroom
in Manhattan just before a
concert.

46:26.384 --> 46:31.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRAD MEHLDAU: Even when I'm
ostensibly accompanying
him, and he's ostensibly taking
the solo,

46:31.689 --> 46:33.524 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
we're still having this
conversation.

46:33.557 --> 46:38.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it may mean, for instance,
that he plays
a melodic idea, and then I
respond to it sort

46:38.195 --> 46:43.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of in real time, and I might
even give him
something back, that then he
responds to again.

46:43.167 --> 46:44.635 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOSHUA REDMAN: I'm always
looking for something.

46:44.669 --> 46:46.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRAD MEHLDAU: And he's kind of
waiting for
it.

46:46.370 --> 46:48.139 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's like, come on, what do you
got?

46:48.172 --> 46:49.106 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

46:49.140 --> 46:50.107 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What do you got?

46:50.141 --> 46:51.409 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BRAD MEHLDAU: Yes.

46:51.442 --> 46:52.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSHUA REDMAN: Well, and often
because I don't
have anything.

46:52.143 --> 46:53.377 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:53.411 --> 46:55.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSHUA REDMAN: I always feel
like I'm -- as
an improviser.

46:55.246 --> 47:01.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I feel a little hamstrung by
this instrument
and its role in jazz, because
it's basically

47:01.385 --> 47:03.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a soloist instrument.

47:03.287 --> 47:08.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I play melodies, maybe some
accompanying harmonies
if there's another horn player,
and then I

47:08.926 --> 47:20.738 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will take a solo, and then I
have to go stand
at the side of the stage.

47:20.771 --> 47:25.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, I have rhythm section
envy because
they get to, like, be in there,
and always

47:25.910 --> 47:29.080 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- you know, they're always
listening, always
reacting.

47:29.113 --> 47:34.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I feel like my best ideas
often don't
come from me.

47:34.418 --> 47:37.855 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
